          "body": "The climax of the wilderness section (8:5) is a hermeneutical key for all suffering: 'thus you are to know in your heart that the LORD your God was disciplining you just as a man disciplines his son.' The father-son analogy does not minimize the wilderness's hardship — Moses has just described it as a 'great and terrible wilderness, with its fiery serpents and scorpions and thirsty ground where there was no water' (8:15). It reinterprets the hardship's motive and trajectory. A father who disciplines his son does not hate him; he is investing in his formation. The goal of the wilderness was not survival but character — specifically, the character of a people who know in their bones that their God is both able to sustain them and worthy of their trust. This analogy is taken up explicitly in Hebrews 12:5-11, which quotes Proverbs 3:11-12 and frames Christian suffering as the same kind of fatherly discipline. John Calvin observed that this passage prevents two equal and opposite errors: despair that interprets hardship as divine abandonment, and presumption that interprets ease as divine approval. Neither suffering nor prosperity is, by itself, the indicator of God's favor — only the covenant relationship, read in the light of God's stated purposes, reveals the truth."
